04816nam a22005895i 9780773599109DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20162016xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a2019394350  a97807735991097 a10.1515/97807735991092doi  a(DE-B1597)655199  a(OCoLC)941433365  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA00aK3248.L36bR39 2016 7aSOC0620002bisacsh1 aRay, Arthur J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAboriginal Rights Claims and the Making and Remaking of History /cArthur J. Ray. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource :b11 maps, 17 images  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Indigenous and Northern Studies ;v8700tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures and Text Boxes -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tTaking Indigenous Peoples’ Lands -- tThe United States Indian Claims Commission -- tLitigating and Negotiating Native Title and Treaty Rights in Canada -- tAnthropologists, Historians, and the Title Claims of Aborigines in Australia -- tThe Waitangi Tribunal and New Zealand History -- tRedressing Race-Based Dispossessions in South Africa -- tThe Métis in Court: Problems of Discrimination, Identity, and Community -- tCourts, Commissions, and Tribunals as Forums for Interpreting and Making History -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aForums such as commissions, courtroom trials, and tribunals that have been established through the second half of the twentieth century to address aboriginal land claims have consequently created a particular way of presenting aboriginal, colonial, and national histories. The history that emerges from these land-claims processes is often criticized for being “presentist” – inaccurately interpreting historical actions and actors through the lens of present-day values, practices, and concerns. In Aboriginal Rights Claims and the Making and Remaking of History, Arthur Ray examines how claims-oriented research is often fitted to the existing frames of indigenous rights law and claims legislation and, as a result, has influenced the development of these laws and legislation. Through a comparative study encompassing the United States, Canada, South Africa, Australia and New Zealand, Ray also explores the ways in which various procedures and settings for claims adjudication have influenced and changed the use of historical evidence, made space for indigenous voices, stimulated scholarly debates about the cultural and historical experiences of indigenous peoples at the time of initial European contact and afterward, and have provoked reactions from politicians and scholars. While giving serious consideration to the flaws and strengths of presentist histories, Aboriginal Rights Claims and the Making and Remaking of History provides communities with essential information on how history is used and how methods are adapted and changed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIndigenous peoplesxClaimsxHistoryy20th century. 0aIndigenous peoplesxColonizationxHistoryy20th century. 0aIndigenous peoplesxGovernment policyxHistoryy20th century. 0aIndigenous peoplesxHistoryy20th century. 0aIndigenous peoplesxLegal status, laws, etcxHistoryy20th century. 0aIndigenous peoplesxLegal status, laws, etc.xHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Indigenous Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311127380808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2016z978311127630440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077359910940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780